On this day in history in 1782, George Washington created the Purple Heart during his time as the commander in chief of the Continental Army during the Revolutionary War. 

He awarded it to only three soldiers during the Revolutionary War. The purple badge allowed soldiers to pass guards without challenge and have their names recorded in the ‚ÄúBook of Merit.‚Äù The award was forgotten until it was reinstated on Washington‚Äôs 200th birthday in 1932. 

Today, the Purple Heart is awarded to soldiers who have been wounded, killed, or prisoners of war. It is the oldest American award for the armed forces.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
For 40 years, "Chevron deference" let unelected bureaucrats interpret laws however they wanted, leading to overregulation.

But Chevron is dead‚Äîand it's time for Congress to do its job again.

I crafted a 150-page blueprint for clawing power back from the administrative state. üßµ https://t.co/TIIgX2sBoi

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Last year, in Loper Bright Enterprises v. Raimondo, the Supreme Court overturned Chevron U.S.A. v. Natural Resources Defense Council‚Äîthe 1984 ruling that gave the administrative state power to interpret the law however it wanted.

It was a seismic win for our constitution. https://t.co/lY9h9uc43v

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
First, the short-term priorities.

Congress must cut funding to the federal bureaucracy‚Äîand utilize the Congressional Review Act to remove as many harmful Biden regulations as possible.

If we don‚Äôt fund it, they can‚Äôt enforce it. That‚Äôs our leverage. Let‚Äôs use it.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Next: Medium-term projects.

‚Ä¢ SOPRA: Codifies de novo judicial review of agency actions

‚Ä¢ ERASER Act: Codifies the current Trump EO requiring agencies to repeal multiple rules for each one one issued

‚Ä¢ REINS Act: No $100M+ rule goes into effect without vote from Congress

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Last Congress, I served as Chair of the Post-Chevron Working Group.

Now, I have authored the first comprehensive post-Chevron strategy‚Äîa roadmap for Congress to retake the lawmaking power it previously gave away to unelected bureaucrats.

Here are the key legislative takeaways:

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Finally‚Äîthe long-term goals: starting new conversations

‚Ä¢ Require regular statutory reauthorization or sunsetting for federal agencies

‚Ä¢ Set hard caps on total regulatory costs

‚Ä¢ Look into a Separation of Powers constitutional amendment to restore the nondelegation doctrine

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
That has to change. So we built a comprehensive guide for lawmakers to write bills that don‚Äôt give bureaucrats loopholes to seize power.

Tight definitions. Clear limits. No more vague ‚Äúweasel words.‚Äù

Name: Schmitt, Eric

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The saga begins with the much-reported battle over illegal deportations that played out in federal court, in the courtroom of Chief Judge Boasberg of the United States District Court for the District of Columbia, a respected veteran of decades on the bench.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Federal judges, particularly senior and respected ones, aren‚Äôt used to being conned, tricked or lied to, particularly not by the government. DOJ‚Äôs conduct in the deportation proceedings caused Boasberg to find probable cause of criminal contempt.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Bove was teed up to become a Trump judge, and in an AMAZING coincidence, two Trump judges on the Court of Appeals stalled the contempt proceedings, allowing Bove to be rushed through confirmation without that factual record of contempt.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: At the center of the mischief was Trump thug lawyer Emil Bove, who would have been a center of attention, and possibly found a contemnor, in contempt hearings, where testimony is taken under oath under penalty of perjury, and with cross-examination.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: We know from well-corroborated whistleblowers (ignored by Judiciary Committee Republicans in their stampede) that had the contempt hearing gone forward, there is abundant reason to believe it would have gone badly for Emil Bove.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text:

text: (As a sidebar, the allegation is that Boasberg spoke generally about violation of court orders by the Trump administration. If that‚Äôs the complaint, in addition to being private, in an internal administrative venue not a judicial one, it has the benefit of being true.)

Name: Houlahan, Chrissy
text:
I hear often from constituents about rising energy costs, the need for infrastructure upgrades, and interest in solar energy resources. Thanks to legislation like the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law passed in 2021 under President Biden, PECO has been able to invest millions of dollars in building resiliency against extreme weather and improve grid flexibility.

In Chester County, PECO is also working to expand energy assistance programs, community solar initiatives, and electric vehicle infrastructure as well as partnering with local workforce development organizations to support training in energy and utility trades. Some of these innovative responses to our ever-increasing demand for electricity here and across the nation will disappear under the Trump Administration which recently terminated $7 billion meant to provide solar power to homes and its recent decision to halt wind turbine energy projects. 

Last month, we set two national records for high energy demand. President Trump's policies are hurting us and making it harder to address the real needs of families, businesses and communities.

Name: Kelly, Mark
text:
I just left a visit to the ICE detention facility in Eloy. There‚Äôs a lot to absorb, but I want to tell you about a woman I met named Maria because her story really shows how messed up all this is. 

She‚Äôs been in the U.S. for twenty years. Has no criminal history. She was detained at the Marine Base in Yuma. Her son is a U.S. Marine stationed there. He‚Äôs married to another Marine. And they have a two-year-old kid, Maria's grandson.  

Maria was in Yuma because her son was leaving for training, her daughter-in-law had a hip surgery, and so they needed help watching her grandson. When she came back to the base after a grocery run, she was detained and reported to CBP. Now, she‚Äôs being held in an ICE facility. 

I remember how proud my parents were watching my brother and I get sworn into the Navy, so I asked her if she had been there when her son graduated from boot camp. She broke down in tears. All she could say was how proud of her son she was.  

That stuck with me. And it should stick with you. And if I have anything to do about it, it will stick with this administration. This woman loves America. Her son is risking her life for America ‚Äì for us. She is the exact type of person we should want in this country. My team and I will keep fighting for her and her family.

As a general rule, when you‚Äôre able to prepare an ex parte injunction‚Äî a one-sided attack‚Äî you‚Äôre going to lead with your absolute best evidence. In this case, the judge fully rejected the accusations and found them insufficient to support any of the allegations.
¬†
Once again, Anthony Sabatini, who was my primary opponent in 2022, should be fighting at the ballot box‚Äî which he lost to me‚Äî but instead, he appears more interested in weaponizing his judicial system against a former political opponent.
¬†
It is tragic the way he continues to use people to serve his political agenda of attacking me. And once again, he has turned up empty-handed, with nothing more than fake news in his latest round of baseless attacks.
¬†
He has not provided sufficient evidence, no facts to support these false claims, and has wasted the time and resources of our hard-working law enforcement officers with yet another politically motivated stunt for his new office.¬†
¬†
We‚Äôve seen this before, when President Trump was relentlessly targeted by political opponents with baseless accusations. The weaponization of the judicial system is an egregious affront to our democracy‚Äî and Sabatini should be ashamed for borrowing tactics from the radical left‚Äôs playbook. Name: Bean, Aaron
text:
üí°Did you know yesterday, August 7th, was National Lighthouse Day?

To celebrate, I attended the Amelia Island Lighthouse Grand Re-Opening. Built in 1838, this is the oldest lighthouse in the state and has stood watch over Florida‚Äôs coastline as a beacon of hope guiding vessels home for nearly two centuries. 

Last year, I got a call from my son who was serving as the Mayor and he informed me the lighthouse needed a new beacon. Our team immediately went to work joining colleagues from Northeast Florida and the U.S. Coast Guard Auxiliary in the effort to refurbish her brilliant beacon. 

Thanks to the dedication of city leaders and the collaboration of our local, state, and federal partners, this historic renovation has come to fruition‚Äîrestoring her beauty and safeguarding her legacy for generations to come.

This lighthouse isn‚Äôt just a landmark to me; it‚Äôs a part of my childhood, a symbol of the community that raised me, and a reminder of how lucky I am to call this place home.

To everyone who contributed to this restoration, THANK YOU!!

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we honor extraordinary individuals and organizations whose service reflects the highest ideals of the American spirit. Today, we celebrate a group that has been a pillar of service for nearly 80 years‚Äîmeet this week‚Äôs Hometown Heroes, VFW Post 6393 Yardley Pennsylvania. 
 
Founded in 1946 by local World War II veterans, Post 6393 has continued to answer the call to serve. With over 200 members, they remain a lifeline for veterans, a partner to families, and a cornerstone of our community. Their work spans generations‚Äîhelping our Vietnam veterans secure long-overdue benefits, welcoming our younger veterans of the Global War on Terrorism, and creating a place where every veteran feels valued, respected, and at home.
 
This year, their unmatched record of service was recognized on the national stage as VFW Post 6393 was named the 2025 Outstanding National Community Service Post of the Year for the Eastern Conference‚Äîan honor awarded to only one post in each region of the country. It is among the highest distinctions in the VFW, recognizing not only the dollars donated, hours volunteered, and miles driven, but the lives lifted, restored, and forever changed.
 
Under Commander Kirk Saboda‚Äôs leadership, Post 6393 has set a new standard for what a modern VFW can be‚Äîforward-looking, inclusive, and deeply engaged in every facet of community life. They deliver free, expert guidance to veterans navigating the VA system, run a home repair program that has restored safety and dignity through more than 60 completed projects for older veterans, and have remodeled their facilities to be fully accessible for all. Through the Code Blue initiative with AHTN, they stand watch on the coldest winter nights, ensuring no homeless veteran‚Äîor civilian‚Äîis left without shelter.
 
That same spirit of service extends seamlessly into our broader community. They sponsor Cub Scout Pack 30 and Venture Crew 6393, host Veterans Night to instill patriotism and civic responsibility in young people, and invite Scouts to take an active role in major community fundraisers, including their annual Classic Car Show and Wrangler Fest. Their poppy campaigns at Easter, Memorial Day, and Veterans Day fuel an emergency relief fund‚Äîready to cover heating bills, urgent home repairs, and other critical needs at a moment‚Äôs notice.
 
Whether folding the flag with a Cub Scout, repairing a veteran‚Äôs home, mentoring the next generation, or standing shoulder-to-shoulder with a neighbor in crisis, Post 6393 lives its creed every single day: ‚ÄúNo one does more for veterans.‚Äù
 
Over the years, I have had the honor of working alongside these extraordinary patriots‚Äîhearing their stories, learning from their hard-earned wisdom, and witnessing the depth of their impact firsthand. Their insight has shaped my work, their friendship is a privilege, and their steadfast partnership in serving our community is one of my greatest honors. I am proud to call these heroes not only partners in service, but true friends.
 
Please join me in congratulating Yardley‚ÄìLower Makefield VFW Post 6393 on this national honor‚Äîand in thanking them for their unwavering example that service to country is a lifelong calling.

text:
Since the days following the attack on October 7, 2023, I‚Äôve been clear: Israel cannot defeat Hamas without a political endgame for Gaza. That‚Äôs a core tenet of successful counterinsurgency operations, as we learned in Iraq and Afghanistan. A military occupation of Gaza with no endgame is a dead end.

Despite pushback from Israel‚Äôs military leadership, the extremists in Netanyahu‚Äôs government see full occupation as a way to cling to power, expel Palestinians, expand settlements, and pave the way for annexation. That is not a plan for peace. Netanyahu‚Äôs statement that Israel does not want to govern Gaza and wants to hand it over to Arab forces is the right idea, but he must agree to, and support, a credible plan for Gaza‚Äôs political future: one that's both free from Hamas and built in the best interest of Palestinians. That is the only road to lasting peace for both Israelis and Palestinians.

In parallel, it‚Äôs critical that the humanitarian needs of Palestinians are addressed immediately. The region doesn‚Äôt just need enough aid to feed the hungry, Israel needs to flood the zone with aid so there‚Äôs no reason for anyone to fight over food or for children to die of starvation.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Today, I joined friends and neighbors at Cafe Chris to honor owner Mary Rodriguez and her granddaughter Erica Lopez with a Congressional Recognition on the one-year anniversary of the caf√©‚Äôs reopening.

Cafe Chris has been serving Pleasanton for over 30 years, but a fire last year forced the hometown favorite to close its doors. If you live in a wildfire-prone area, take steps now to protect yourself, your family, and your property:
 
‚úÖ Sign up for local emergency alerts from Cal Fire and your county OES
‚úÖ Prepare an emergency supply kit with essentials, medications, documents, and pet needs
‚úÖ Clear flammable vegetation and debris from around your home
‚úÖ Park your car facing your evacuation route and keep the tank full
‚úÖ Keep doors and windows closed but unlocked for firefighter access
‚úÖ Have at least two evacuation routes planned, by foot and by car

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 2018, 28-year-old Richard Russell ‚Äî remembered as "Sky King" ‚Äî borrowed an airplane from Seattle-Tacoma International Airport for a joyride before crashing into a remote island.

Russell had worked as a ground crew member, partly so he could visit his family in Alaska more often. Though he had no formal flight training other than playing video games, he developed a deep fascination with aviation. On the evening of August 10th, he gained access to an aircraft and took off smoothly, only drawing attention once fellow employees realized something was wrong.

During his flight, Russell flew over Mount Rainier and the Olympic Mountains, did a barrel roll, and even requested GPS coordinates for a recently sighted orca and calf.

Air traffic controllers, two F-15 fighter jets, and a civilian pilot tried to persuade him to land, but their efforts were unsuccessful. When the plane eventually ran out of fuel, Russell guided it into Ketron Island. His death was ruled a suicide, possibly linked to past brain injuries from multiple concussions.

His family remembered him as ‚Äúa faithful husband, a loving man, and a good friend‚Ä¶ He was right in saying that there are so many people who loved him.‚Äù Rest in peace, Sky King.

Name: Guthrie, Brett
text:
.@GovAndyBeshear, enough with the fear mongering. Here‚Äôs the truth about how the One, Big, Beautiful Bill will strengthen Medicaid for Kentucky‚Äôs most vulnerable. ‚¨áÔ∏è

‚û°Ô∏è The ‚Äúcoverage loss‚Äù you cite stems from the state‚Äôs provider tax payments. The state made a commitment to fund 10% of Medicaid ‚Äì the federal government will continue to cover our 90%, and actually increase funding. The federal government will continue to honor our commitment.

‚û°Ô∏è Our bill does nothing to impact Medicaid benefits for mothers and children.

‚û°Ô∏è The people who will lose access to Medicaid under our bill are able-bodied individuals who choose not to work, or are already ineligible to receive benefits under the program. This plan is simply the elimination of waste, fraud, and abuse in Medicaid. 

‚û°Ô∏è You claim that 35 rural Kentucky hospitals will close as a result of our bill. Last week, I visited several rural hospitals in my district that you claim will close because of our bill. Every single one of them has said they will stay open providing care to Kentuckians.

Again, enough with the attempts to scare people. Being a leader means making responsible decisions for taxpayers and the most vulnerable in our Commonwealth. Our bill does exactly that.

Name: Cantwell, Maria
text:
Today is another absurd attempt by the President to use emergency powers where they don‚Äôt apply.
¬†
DC‚Äôs violent crime rate has been going down for the last decade.
¬†
One of best ways to help cities fight crime is funding community policing programs that have reduced¬†violent crime rates in some cities by as much as 50%.
¬†
But the President has cut these community programs, Byrne JAG, and other grants by $500 million.
¬†
The U.S. Attorney General should let DC mayor Muriel Bowser do her job and the FBI should do theirs. Which means the FBI fighting money laundering, sex trafficking and combatting drug trafficking.¬†
¬†
If the President really wanted to fight crime in our cities, he would create a Fentanyl Task Force with the Department of Homeland Security, Department of Justice and local law enforcement sharing resources and working collaboratively to tackle this scourge. This approach is showing great success on one of our worse crime problems--Fentanyl.
¬†
It may take a while for the courts to act on this overreach by President Trump who is simply trying to project power. But the American people know there are better ways to solve their problems than this authoritarian move.

text:
A recent report from the @USCBO confirms what we already knew ‚Äì the partisan budget passed last month funds tax breaks to the wealthiest households by slashing critical health care and nutrition programs that everyday families in South Texas rely on.

While the top 10% will receive $13,600 more annually, the lowest 10% of earners will lose $1,200 every year largely due to cuts to Medicaid and SNAP. These cuts mean fewer people will get the care and food assistance they need, making it harder for working families, seniors, and the most vulnerable to make ends meet.

Instead of protecting essential services, this budget takes from those who can least afford it to reward those who need it least, which is why I voted against these dangerous cuts. I'll continue fighting for responsible, bipartisan solutions that strengthen our economy and put the needs of South Texan families first.

Name: Gallego, Ruben
text:
Today I met with the family of Kelly Yu ‚Äî a mother, wife, business owner, and job creator who is being held in ICE detention here in Arizona.

Kelly owns multiple restaurants and has spent decades contributing to our state‚Äôs economy and community. Arizona is not safer because she‚Äôs in detention, and it will not be better if she‚Äôs deported.

Kelly fled China in fear of her country‚Äôs one-child policy. Since then, she has done everything right to try and earn citizenship. But a few months ago, when she went to her routine check-in with immigration officials, she was handcuffed on the spot and taken away from her husband and daughter ‚Äî both U.S. citizens.

Why is Trump doing this? It‚Äôs not about safety. In fact, we are less safe. Going after people like Kelly is a waste of resources. It‚Äôs pulling agents away from fighting child exploitation and drug trafficking. He‚Äôs doing it just to meet some arbitrary deportation quota. 

Voters didn‚Äôt elect Trump to tear families like Kelly‚Äôs apart. Kelly is not a threat. She is not a criminal. She is not the ‚Äúbad guy.‚Äù This needs to stop.
